3
00:00:19,280 --> 00:00:27,760
I'm Neil and I'm Tim. So we had an argument just before we started the show. We did Tim.

4
00:00:28,720 --> 00:00:31,200
No hard feelings? None.

5
00:00:32,160 --> 00:00:38,640
No hard feelings is something you say to somebody you have argued with to say you'd still like to be friends.

6
00:00:39,439 --> 00:00:46,079
We often fall out over silly things like who's going to introduce the show or who's going to choose the quiz question.

7
00:00:46,079 --> 00:00:49,439
But we understand each other. That's the important thing, isn't it?

8
00:00:50,400 --> 00:00:55,680
To fall out with somebody by the way is another way of saying to argue or disagree with them.

9
00:00:56,320 --> 00:00:59,519
Do you know that you wave your arms around a lot when you're arguing Tim?

10
00:01:00,159 --> 00:01:03,840
No. I didn't know I did that. That isn't very British.

11
00:01:04,480 --> 00:01:11,200
I know. Using gestures or movements you make with your hands or your head to express what you

12
00:01:11,200 --> 00:01:15,920
are thinking or feeling is common in some countries but not in others.

13
00:01:16,719 --> 00:01:21,439
Then there are some movements like shaking your head which mostly means no.

14
00:01:21,519 --> 00:01:25,439
But in some countries can mean the opposite. That's right.

15
00:01:25,439 --> 00:01:29,519
In which country does shaking your head mean yes Tim?

16
00:01:29,519 --> 00:01:37,759
Is it a Greece, B Japan or C Bulgaria? No idea. I'll guess Greece?

17
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:42,799
I do know that in India people shake their heads to mean lots of different things.

18
00:01:42,799 --> 00:01:47,280
There are plenty of gestures you need to be careful with when you're meeting and greeting people

19
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:53,519
from a culture that's different to your own to avoid offending people or making an awkward faux pas.

20
00:01:53,519 --> 00:01:59,920
If you make a faux pas it means you say or do something embarrassing in a social situation.

21
00:02:00,480 --> 00:02:07,439
For example, everyday use of the thumbs up signal might offend people from the Middle East.

22
00:02:07,439 --> 00:02:10,800
And to offend means to make somebody angry or upset.

23
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:17,840
Now let's hear from business professor Aaron Mayer talking about how easy it is to misunderstand

24
